sols_latex:
There are actually two cases we have to consider here, if \emph{p=1} and
if $p\neq1$. We will see why below:

First assume that $p\neq1$. Given the function $y=f(x)=\frac{1}{x^p}$ on
the interval {[}1,\emph{B}{]}, the area between this curve and the
\emph{x}-axis is

\begin{align*}
A &= \int_{1}^{B}\frac{1}{x^p}dx = \int_{1}^{B}x^{-p}dx \\
&= \left [ \frac{x^{-p+1}}{-p+1} \right ]_{1}^{B} = \frac{1}{1-p} \left ( B^{1-p}-1 \right)
\end{align*}

Note that, if \emph{p=1}, then the above does not work because we would
divide by \emph{1-p=0}.

Hence we treat \emph{p=1} separately. The function becomes
$y=f(x)=\frac{1}{x}$ and on the interval {[}1,\emph{B}{]}, the area
between this curve and the \emph{x}-axis is

\begin{align*}
A &= \int_{1}^{B}\frac{1}{x}dx\\
&= \left [ \ln{x} \right ]_{1}^{B} = \ln{B}
\end{align*}

So our final answer is

\begin{align*}
A = \int_1^B \frac{1}{x^p}\,dx=
\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{1-p} \left ( B^{1-p}-1 \right),&p\neq{1}\\
\ln{B},&p=1
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

